Euler's Theorem states that

\begin{align*}
a^{\phi(b)} &\equiv 1 \mod{b} \\
b^{\phi(a)} &\equiv 1 \mod{a}
\end{align*}

Translating the above, there exist integers \emph{s} and \emph{t} such
that

\begin{align*}
a^{\phi(b)} -1 &= bs\\
b^{\phi(a)} -1 &= at
\end{align*}

Taking the products of the left hand sides of the equation and the right
hand sides of the equation yields (below we have flipped the sides of
the equations)

\begin{align*}
abst &= (a^{\phi(b)} -1)(b^{\phi(a)} -1) = a^{\phi(b)}b^{\phi(a)} - a^{\phi(b)} - b^{\phi(a)} + 1
\end{align*}

As $\displaystyle \phi(a)$ and $\displaystyle \phi(b)$ are at least one,
we have that

\begin{align*}
0 &\equiv  - a^{\phi(b)} - b^{\phi(a)} + 1 \mod{ab}
\end{align*}

and hence we get the required result. For the last part, we have

$\displaystyle 5^{8} \equiv (5^{2})^{4} \equiv 25^{4} \equiv 9^{4} \equiv (9^{2})^{2} \equiv 81^{2} \equiv 1^{2} \equiv 1 \mod{16}$

(or easier, notice that $\displaystyle \phi(16) = 8$ so Euler's theorem
gives the same result) Thus as the number is 1, its inverse it itself.

